        "content": "### 1. Assuming result order matches submission order\n```python\n# BAD ŌĆö results may come back in any order\nresults = list(client.messages.batches.results(batch_id))\nfor i, result in enumerate(results):\n    original_docs[i][\"summary\"] = result  # WRONG ŌĆö mismatched\n\n# GOOD ŌĆö always match on custom_id\nresults = {}\nfor entry in client.messages.batches.results(batch_id):\n    results[entry.custom_id] = entry.result\n```\n\n### 2. Fire-and-forget without tracking\n```python\n# BAD ŌĆö no way to recover if your process crashes\nbatch = client.messages.batches.create(requests=requests)\n# ... process crashes, batch_id lost\n\n# GOOD ŌĆö persist batch_id immediately\nbatch = client.messages.batches.create(requests=requests)\nsave_to_db(batch_id=batch.id, status=\"submitted\", request_count=len(requests))\n```\n\n### 3. Not handling partial failures\n```python\n# BAD ŌĆö assumes all succeeded\nfor entry in client.messages.batches.results(batch_id):\n    process(entry.result.message.content[0].text)  # Crashes on errors\n\n# GOOD ŌĆö check result type\nfor entry in client.messages.batches.results(batch_id):\n    if entry.result.type == \"succeeded\":\n        process(entry.result.message.content[0].text)\n    elif entry.result.type == \"errored\":\n        log_error(entry.custom_id, entry.result.error)\n    elif entry.result.type == \"expired\":\n        requeue(entry.custom_id)\n```\n\n### 4. Batching when you should stream\nIf users are waiting ŌåÆ use streaming. If processing data ŌåÆ use batching.\nThere's no in-between ŌĆö batch API has no latency guarantee."
