        "heading": "Common Mistakes & Gotchas",
        "content": "### 1. Defaulting to Opus \"just to be safe\"\n```\nReality check: Run the same 50 classification prompts through Haiku and Opus.\nTypical result: Haiku matches Opus on 95%+ of deterministic tasks.\nYou're paying 5x for no quality gain.\n```\n\n### 2. Never evaluating whether downgrade works\n```python\n# BUILD THIS: A/B eval before committing to a model tier\n# Run 100 representative prompts through each model\n# Score outputs (automated or human review)\n# Only use the expensive model where quality actually differs\n```\n\n### 3. Using Sonnet for pure classification\nIf the output is a label from a fixed set, Haiku handles it. Sonnet's extra reasoning capability is wasted on `{\"category\": \"billing\"}`.\n\n### 4. Ignoring the cascade approach\nMost teams pick ONE model and use it everywhere. The cascade pattern (try cheap ŌåÆ escalate) captures 80%+ of savings with minimal complexity.\n\n### 5. Not tracking model usage\nIf you don't instrument which model handles which requests, you can't optimize. Add logging from day one.\n\n```python\nimport logging\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(\"model_routing\")\n\ndef tracked_call(client, model, **kwargs):\n    response = client.messages.create(model=model, **kwargs)\n    logger.info(\n        \"api_call\",\n        extra={\n            \"model\": model,\n            \"input_tokens\": response.usage.input_tokens,\n            \"output_tokens\": response.usage.output_tokens,\n            \"cost\": calculate_cost(model, response.usage),\n        }\n    )\n    return response\n```"
